Bay Buccaneers","Detroit Lions","Tampa Bay Buccaneers @ Detroit Lions","NFL"],"story":"DETROIT --  The <a href=\"https://apnews.com/hub/detroit-lions\"><a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/det/detroit-lions\">Detroit Lions</a></a> have bounced back from losses better than any <a href=\"https://apnews.com/hub/nfl\">NFL</a> team for nearly three years.\n\n\r\n              Detroit has not dropped consecutive games in the regular season since coach Dan Campbell's second season got off to a shaky start, falling to 1-6 on Oct. 30, 2022.\n\n\r\n              The Lions' 50-game stretch without back-to-back setbacks is the longest in the league since Green Bay went 53 games without consecutive losses from late in the 2018 season through the 2022 season, according to Sportradar, and the next-longest active run is 18 games by the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/lar/los-angeles-rams\">Los Angeles Rams</a>.\n\n\r\n              Theyre a resilient group, Campbell said. They know how to overcome adversity. They dont like losing and they go back to work to fix the things that need to be fixed.\n\n\r\n              If Detroit (4-2) does not address problems it had on both sides of the ball in last week's loss to Kansas City, its remarkable run may end against the NFC-leading <a href=\"https://apnews.com/hub/tampa-bay-buccaneers\"><a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/tb/tampa-bay-buccaneers\">Tampa Bay Buccaneers</a></a> (5-1) on Monday night at home.\n\n\r\n              Weve got our hands full, Campbell said.\n\n\r\n              After the Buccaneers became the first team in NFL history with four wins by three or fewer points in the first five games of season, they <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/49ers-buccaneers-score-4ff79691b71f6d6e563c043b127521d7\">beat San Francisco</a> 30-19 last week.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Short-handed</hl2>\r\n              Detroit's banged-up secondary took another hit when the NFL <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/lions-chiefs-brian-branch-suspension-8c3121758abd604015dc220a9a884d17\">suspended safety <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4692025/brian-branch\">Brian Branch</a></a> for punching Chiefs receiver <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3120348/juju-smith-schuster\">JuJu Smith-Schuster</a> on Sunday night and setting off a postgame melee.\n\n\r\n              The Lions have five players in their secondary on injured reserve and they held defensive backs <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4360383/kerby-joseph\">Kerby Joseph</a>, <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4592837/terrion-arnold\">Terrion Arnold</a> and <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3123938/avonte-maddox\">Avonte Maddox</a> out of practice with injuries on Thursday.\n\n\r\n              Tampa Bay is expecting to be without three of its top receivers, but the position group may get a boost with the return of six-time Pro Bowl receiver <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/tampa-bay-buccaneers-mike-evans-919d12693b619f51ec0b2aff21f6fe04\"><a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/16737/mike-evans\">Mike Evans</a></a>. He was limited in practice on Thursday after missing three games with a hamstring injury.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>They're No. 1 </hl2>\r\n              Both quarterbacks, Detroit's <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3046779/jared-goff\">Jared Goff</a> and Tampa Bay's <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3052587/baker-mayfield\">Baker Mayfield</a>, were drafted No. 1 overall by another team that traded them.\n\n\r\n              \"Can recognize that theres some dark days in that transition and coming out the other side of it for both of us, Goff said.\n\n\r\n              The Los Angeles Rams kicked off the 2016 draft by taking Goff and after five seasons, including one that ended at the Super Bowl, they dealt him in a blockbuster deal for <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/12483/matthew-stafford\">Matthew Stafford</a>.\n\n\r\n              Cleveland selected Mayfield first overall in 2018 and traded him four years later to Carolina. The Panthers released him later that year and he finished the 2022 season with the Rams. The Bucs gave him another chance by signing him in 2023 and he has made the most of the opportunity, reviving his career.\n\n\r\n              Both of them have overcome a lot, Campbell said.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Rachaads role</hl2>\r\n              <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4697815/rachaad-white\">Rachaad White</a> went from being Tampa Bay's primary back to splitting time with <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4596448/bucky-irving\">Bucky Irving</a> last season. With Irving out the past two games, White has 157 scrimmage yards and three rushing touchdowns.\n\n\r\n              Rachaad made some really, really good plays, Mayfield said.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Return of the mack</hl2>\r\n              <hl2 />\r\n              Detroit defensive tackle <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4361662/alim-mcneill\">Alim McNeill</a>, who signed a <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/detroit-lions-alim-mcneill-contract-5e21c36d5c00011202989b9e4fce5c90\">$97 million contract extension</a> a year ago, is expected to play for the first time since tearing the ACL in his right knee late last season.\n\n\r\n              It's going to be a big day, a big deal, in the back of my head, he said.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Sack attack</hl2>\r\n              The Buccaneers had 10 sacks in the first five games before registering six against <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4241464/mac-jones\">Mac Jones</a> in a win over the 49ers last week. They recorded a sack on 15.4% of dropbacks. Even more impressive, Tampa Bay didnt have to blitz much to get pressure.\n\n\r\n              It all starts up front for us, Bucs coach Todd Bowles said. If we can get off the ball and you dont have to blitz and you can go with four (rushers) and they work together, were a pretty good defense.\n\n\r\n              Linebacker <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4686334/yaya-diaby\">Yaya Diaby</a> had two sacks on Jones and leads the team with three. Texans @ Seattle Seahawks","Seattle Seahawks","Houston Texans","NFL"],"story":"Now the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/sea/seattle-seahawks\">Seattle Seahawks</a> have to figure out how to win consistently at home. \n\n\r\n              Seattle is 3-0 on the road this season but 1-2 at Lumen Field, a loud stadium that not so long ago was one of the teams prized advantages. \n\n\r\n              The Seahawks host the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/hou/houston-texans\">Houston Texans</a> (2-3) on Monday night, hoping to get some of that Lumen Field mojo going. \n\n\r\n              The home slump became apparent last season, when the Seahawks went 3-6 at Lumen, their worst record in Seattle since 2008. \n\n\r\n              We have to win at home, We have to defend our home turf. We know that, Seahawks coach Mike Macdonald said after the Seahawks fell 38-35 to Tampa Bay in Seattle two weeks ago. \n\n\r\n              \"Its really important that we play better at home. Its been an important emphasis since I was hired. Hasnt come to life yet. Were determined to make it come to life.\n\n\r\n              Fortunately for the Seahawks, they're winning on the road. Seattle was coming off a 20-12 win at Jacksonville, which extended the team's franchise record to nine straight road wins. \n\n\r\n              Quarterback <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3912547/sam-darnold\">Sam Darnold</a> threw for 295 yards and a pair of touchdowns in the victory. <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4430878/jaxon-smith-njigba\">Jaxon Smith-Njigba</a> finished with eight catches for 162 yards and a 61-yard TD reception in the second quarter.\n\n\r\n              Houston had a bye week following a 44-10 road win over the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/bal/baltimore-ravens\">Baltimore Ravens</a> before the break. <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4432577/cj-stroud\">C.J. Stroud</a> was the AFC Offensive Player of the Week after throwing for 244 yards and a season-high four touchdowns in the victory. \n\n\r\n              The Texans lost their first three games of the season, but have rebounded with a pair of wins. \n\n\r\n              Its still early in the season,\" Texans coach DeMeco Ryans said. \"A lot of teams had a lot of really good starts to the season. But we all know, and its our focus, its all about how you finish the season. Its all about how your team grows throughout the season. Just because you have a great start doesnt mean its going to be a great finish. You just continue to work, control what you can control and you truly focus on one game at a time. Thats all that matters. \n\n\r\n              <hl2>Doing it all</hl2>\r\n              Safety <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4241223/jalen-pitre\">Jalen Pitre</a> is off to a great start this season and leads the Texans with three interceptions after he had two in Houstons game against the Ravens. The fourth-year player does a little bit of everything for the Texans and Ryans said hes one of the reasons their defense has been successful this season.\n\n\r\n              Whether thats blitzing, whether its playing in coverage, whether its playing back deep  all three levels of the defense, Jalen provides us that flexibility to be able to move him around wherever we need to put him each week, Ryans said. So, to have a player who is as smart as he is and as reliable as he is, it really gives you a comfort as a play-caller.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Closing it out</hl2>\r\n              Seattle held Jacksonville to 273 yards, including just 59 yards rushing. The defense had seven sacks and forced three straight fourth-quarter punts. \n\n\r\n              Macdonald said it was important for the D to prove it could close out games.\n\n\r\n              Its been an emphasis for us, Macdonald said. We werent shying away from it. Our guys were awesome. I think you could sense it on the sideline that they wanted the opportunity to go out there and go play, and thats all you can ask for as a coach.\"\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Chubb and Marks</hl2>\r\n              The Texans have used both <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3128720/nick-chubb\">Nick Chubb</a> and rookie <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4429059/woody-marks\">Woody Marks</a> at running back this season with star <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3116385/joe-mixon\">Joe Mixon</a> out indefinitely with a foot injury. Chubb leads the team with 249 yards rushing and two touchdowns and Marks has 137 yards rushing and a TD run. Marks has also been a playmaker out of the backfield and has 96 yards receiving with another score.\n\n\r\n              The Texans have also been impressed with the blocking of Marks, a fourth-round pick from USC.\n\n\r\n              Hes put it on tape that hes a violent protector and can get underneath people and knows where to go, offensive coordinator Nick Caley said. So, Ive been very pleased with his development. Its been steady since hes been here, and well just continue to keep it on that trajectory.\n\n\r\n              ------\n\n\r\n              AP Sports Writer Kristie Rieken in Houston contributed to this report. \n\n\r\n              ------\n\n\r\n              AP NFL: <a Steelers","Cincinnati Bengals","Pittsburgh Steelers @ Cincinnati Bengals","NFL"],"story":"CINCINNATI --  Mike Tomlin wondered this week why the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/cle/cleveland-browns\">Cleveland Browns</a> traded <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/11252/joe-flacco\">Joe Flacco</a> to their AFC North rival, the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/cin/cincinnati-bengals\">Cincinnati Bengals</a>.\n\n\r\n              On Thursday night, Flacco proved Tomlin's worst fears to be well founded.\n\n\r\n              Flacco passed for 342 yards and three touchdowns as he rallied Cincinnati to a 33-31 victory. <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4360234/evan-mcpherson\">Evan McPherson</a> had four field goals, the last a 36-yarder with seven seconds remaining to put the Bengals on top and snap a four-game losing streak.\n\n\r\n              The 40-year-old Flacco completed 31 of 47 passes in his second Cincinnati start after being acquired Oct. 7, and outdueled 41-year-old <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/8439/aaron-rodgers\">Aaron Rodgers</a> in only the third regular-season game between starting quarterbacks in their 40s.\n\n\r\n              Bengals fans were chanting Thank you Cleveland! Thank you Cleveland! when Flacco appeared on Prime Video's postgame set on the field, which brought a smile to coach Zac Taylor's face.\n\n\r\n              Our fans are happy, and Im happy,\" Taylor said. Its a big victory. We needed this. It had been a long time since we won.\"\n\n\r\n              Cincinnati led most of the second half, but Rodgers gave Pittsburgh a 31-30 advantage with 2:31 remaining on a 68-yard touchdown pass to <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4361411/pat-freiermuth\">Pat Freiermuth</a>. \n\n\r\n              On second-and-20, Rodgers rolled left and found Freiermuth open downfield. The fifth-year tight end caught the ball at the Bengals 36 after getting separation from safety <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4240575/geno-stone\">Geno Stone</a> and scored his second touchdown.\n\n\r\n              I told him to be ready. I saw something on the pictures on the sideline in the first half. So at halftime I pulled him aside. I had a nice shot down the middle, said Rodgers, who went 22 of 32 for 244 yards with four touchdowns and two interceptions. \n\n\r\n              That set the stage for the 23rd fourth-quarter comeback of Flaccos 18-year career. \n\n\r\n              Flacco led the Bengals (3-4) 52 yards in eight plays, including completions of 15 and 18 yards to JaMarr Chase got Cincinnati into Pittsburgh territory. Flacco then found <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4239993/tee-higgins\">Tee Higgins</a> for a 28-yard gain to the Steelers 5 with 1:39 remaining to put the Bengals well within McPhersons range.\n\n\r\n              Its very fun. Its because of games like this that we do what we do,\" Flacco said.\n\n\r\n              Chase had a franchise-record 16 receptions for 161 yards and a TD, making him the fourth receiver in NFL history with two games of at least 14 catches in a single season. Higgins finished with six catches for 96 yards and a score. <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4036131/noah-fant\">Noah Fant</a> also had a TD reception.\n\n\r\n              The Bengals scored on seven of their last eight possessions and won for the first time since <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3915511/joe-burrow\">Joe Burrow</a> went down with a toe injury Sept. 14. <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3886812/jake-browning\">Jake Browning</a> struggled in his three starts after Burrow's injury, prompting the Bengals to acquire Flacco.\n\n\r\n              Last week, it seemed we had finally figured out how it was going to be with Flacco and the offensive line. And today we showed what were capable of,\" Chase said.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4362238/chase-brown\">Chase Brown</a> had 108 rushing yards on 11 carries, the second 100-yard game of his career.\n\n\r\n              Freiermuth had four catches for 106 yards for the Steelers (4-2). <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4569987/jaylen-warren\">Jaylen Warren</a> ran for 127 yards on 16 carries.\n\n\r\n              I just thought the first half we allowed them to run the ball too much,\" Tomlin said. Then we turned the ball over a couple of times, and that just kind of set a negative trajectory. Were fighting uphill the rest of the way.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Bengals rally in second quarter</hl2>\r\n              Pittsburgh jumped out to a 10-0 lead on <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/17372/chris-boswell\">Chris Boswell</a>'s 41-yard field goal early in the second quarter before Rodgers' passes was picked off on consecutive drives.\n\n\r\n              Cincinnati scored a touchdown in the first half for the first time in five games with 4:42 remaining in the first half when Flacco found Chase in the left corner of the end zone for an 8-yard score.\n\n\r\n              The Bengals then converted both of Rodgers interceptions into points. On the first play of the next drive, <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4567098/jordan-battle\">Jordan Battle</a> picked off a deep ball intended for Metcalf at the Bengals 24. Three plays later, Flaccos 29-yard quick slant to Higgins gave Cincinnati its first lead since the first quarter of the Week 4 Monday night game at Denver.\n\n\r\n              After <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4036211/dj-turner\">DJ Turner</a> picked off Flaccos pass along the left sideline at the Cincinnati 30 with 40 seconds remaining, McPherson booted a 49-yarder to make it 17-10 at halftime.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>All day and night</hl2>\r\n              The Steelers scored a touchdown on an opening drive for the third time this season when <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3054212/jonnu-smith\">Jonnu Smith</a> caught a 10-yard pass from Rodgers with 10:51 remaining in the first quarter.\n\n\r\n              Rodgers held onto the ball for 8.598 seconds before connecting with Smith in the end zone. It was Rodgers longest time to throw on a completion since the NFLs Next Gen Stats started tracking in 2016.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Injuries</hl2>\r\n              Bengals: DE <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3052743/trey-hendrickson\">Trey Hendrickson</a> was inactive due to a hip injury he suffered during the first half of last week at Green Bay.\n\n\r\n href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/lar/los-angeles-rams\">Los Angeles Rams</a> quarterback threw five touchdown passes in a 35-7 victory over the <a get a sword or something? a smiling Stafford asked.\n\n\r\n              No, but Stafford and the Rams do get to fly home with a 5-2 record  their best start since their Super Bowl-winning season in soccer.\n\n\r\n              Stafford, who has thrown 12 touchdowns with no interceptions in his past four games, also connected with rookie receiver <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/rams-puka-nacua-out-jaguars-becca36ee7079aad99153d426b2293ee\">missed the game</a> with an ankle injury.\n\n\r\n              We saw a few opportune moments to go and take advantage of some 1-on-1s, said Adams, who noted that he and Stafford had been exchanging extra text messages in recent weeks and talking through certain things.\"\n\n\r\n              Adams became the second player to score three touchdowns in an international game. The NFL said the first was <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/9614/marcedes-lewis\">Marcedes Lewis</a>, who had three in Jacksonville's 44-7 win over the Ravens at Wembley in 2017.\n\n\r\n              Adams, who caught two touchdown passes in the first half, then added a third on a 1-yard jump ball that sent Jags fans to the exits.\n\n\r\n              Stafford completed 21 of 33 passes for 182 yards. Jags quarterback <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4360310/trevor-lawrence\">Trevor Lawrence</a> finished 23 of 48 for 296 yards and the touchdown pass to Hunter.\n\n\r\n              In 2014, Stafford engineered Detroits 22-21 comeback win over the Falcons after trailing 21-0 at halftime.\n\n\r\n              Its a blast. Sometimes travel is tough, but once you get out here, the fans are great, people are great, the 37-year-old quarterback said.\n\n\r\n              The Jaguars allowed seven sacks and committed 13 penalties for 119 yards.\n\n\r\n              Im not going to stand up here and blame these players, it starts with me, Jags coach Liam Coen said. You wouldnt have guessed that we were here for a week, prepared, ready to go play in this atmosphere by looking at it in terms of the way we started the game.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Hunter gets first TD</hl2>\r\n              The only highlight for the Jaguars (4-3) was rookie two-way star <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4685415/travis-hunter\">Travis Hunter</a> getting <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/travis-hunter-jaguars-touchdown-d11b665125c50389a75221669336a856\">his first NFL touchdown</a>. It made the score 28-7 in the fourth quarter.\n\n\r\n              Hunter had his best day as a pro, catching eight passes for 101 yards and the score.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Siu party at Wembley</hl2>\r\n              Despite <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/jaguars-rams-london-0230d07103033d0b079c21ab27563f35\">arriving in London on Saturday morning</a>, the Rams looked plenty fresh by scoring three first-half touchdowns.\n\n\r\n              Mumpfield scored the first and Adams the next two. Both hit the Siu celebration made famous by Portugal soccer star Cristiano Ronaldo.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"https://x.com/RamsNFL/status/1979908200024404262\">Mumpfield's celebration</a> came after the rookie receiver scored his first NFL touchdown  on just his second career catch  a 5-yard reception at the back of the end zone to cap a 13-play, 60-yard opening drive.\n\n\r\n              Five different players caught passes on the Rams opening drive.\n\n\r\n              We spread the ball around a bunch today, Stafford said.\n\n\r\n              On the second drive, Stafford hit Adams on a quick fade for a 2-yard touchdown pass and a 14-0 lead before the end of the first quarter. The star receiver then gave <a href=\"https://x.com/NFLUKIRE/status/1979913005568500137\">his version of the siu</a>.\n\n\r\n              Jags CB <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3045207/jourdan-lewis\">Jourdan Lewis</a> was in coverage on both TDs.\n\n\r\n              Adams then caught a 1-yard touchdown pass before the end of the half to make it 21-0. No siu that time, though.\n\n\r\n              But Adams got <a href=\"https://x.com/NFLUKIRE/status/1979950533629854062\">most of the offense to do one</a> after his third touchdown.\n\n\r\n              Fergusons 31-yard touchdown reception on fourth-and-1 made the score 28-0 early in the fourth.\n\n\r\n              Rams linebacker <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4567123/byron-young\">Byron Young</a> <a href=\"https://x.com/TheLARamsPR/status/1979913827417288958\">extended his sack streak</a> to nine regular-season games.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Key injuries</hl2>\r\n              Rams: <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/rams-puka-nacua-out-jaguars-becca36ee7079aad99153d426b2293ee\">Nacua (ankle) had been ruled out</a> earlier this week. RT <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/2515613/rob-havenstein\">Rob Havenstein</a> (ankle) missed his third straight game.\n\n\r\n              Jaguars: WR <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4361577/dyami-brown\">Dyami Brown</a> was slow to get up after his 39-yard reception in the third quarter. ... CB Jourdan Lewis was checked after a tackle late in first half ... S <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/2970716/eric-murray\">Eric Murray</a> and WR <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3134353/tim-patrick\">Tim Patrick</a> were ruled out of the game early in the fourth quarter... NFL interception leader <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4243256/devin-lloyd\">Devin Lloyd</a> (calf) didn't make the trip.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Up next</hl2>\r\n              Rams: Bye and then host the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/no/new-orleans-saints\">New Orleans Saints</a> at SoFi Stadium in Week 9.\n\n\r\n              Jaguars: Bye and then visit the <a Orleans Saints @ Chicago Bears","Chicago Bears","New Orleans Saints","NFL"],"story":"CHICAGO --  As much as Dennis Allen downplayed going against his former team, his players weren't buying it. This one had to mean a little more.\n\n\r\n              Allens defense dominated, and the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/chi/chicago-bears\">Chicago Bears</a> beat the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/no/new-orleans-saints\">New Orleans Saints</a> 26-14 on Sunday for their fourth straight win.\n\n\r\n              Allen, the Bears defensive coordinator, was facing the Saints for the first time since they fired him as head coach midway through last season after 2 1/2 years. \n\n\r\n              He didn't make it about himself this entire week, he didn't mention anything about it, safety Kevin Byard said. But just me being a veteran, I know. This meant a lot for him.\n\n\r\n              Allen spent 15 of the past 20 years in New Orleans either as an assistant under Sean Payton or head coach. He was part of a Super Bowl-winning staff.\n\n\r\n              Allen was the Saints' defensive coordinator for six years before getting promoted in 2022 when Payton retired. He led New Orleans to an 18-25 record with no playoff appearances before he was fired last November.\n\n\r\n              I know what it feels like to go against your old team, said veteran linebacker <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3929950/tremaine-edmunds\">Tremaine Edmunds</a>, who had a sack and an interception. He probably had a lot of emotions into it. I'm glad he was able to celebrate and smile after the game.\n\n\r\n              Allen brushed this off as another game during the week. But it was clear he was feeling pretty good afterward.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"https://x.com/ChicagoBears/status/1980019929765056912\">Allen got the game ball from coach Ben Johnson</a>, then told the team: Sometimes, the good Lord just has a freakin' plan for you that you don't know about. And sometimes, you ain't good enough for somewhere else. That's perfectly fine. I love being here. I love being with this group of guys.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Take it away</hl2>\r\n              The Bears forced four turnovers in their fourth straight game with three or more, giving them 16 takeaways this season. They had four sacks and three interceptions against <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4426339/spencer-rattler\">Spencer Rattler</a>.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"https://x.com/ChicagoBears/status/1979958047934923260\"><a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3134690/montez-sweat\">Montez Sweat</a> set the tone with an early strip-sack</a> that led to a field goal. <a href=\"https://x.com/ChicagoBears/status/1979969086428713388\"><a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4570470/nahshon-wright\">Nahshon Wright</a> set up the games first touchdown with a long interception return</a>, and the Bears (4-2) overcame a spotty performance by <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4431611/caleb-williams\">Caleb Williams</a> to match their best streak since the 2018 NFC North championship team closed the regular season with four straight wins. They also had a much easier time after winning 25-24 at both Las Vegas and Washington.\n\n\r\n              New Orleans (1-6) continued its worst start since opening 1-7 in 1999 under then-coach Mike Ditka, the Hall of Famer and Super Bowl-winning coach with the Bears.\n\n\r\n              We cant stop,\" running back <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3054850/alvin-kamara\">Alvin Kamara</a> said. \"We got to find some energy, find some inspiration. Everybody got to just dig deep and find that want-to.\n\n\r\n              Williams completed 15 of 26 passes for 172 yards and an interception. But Chicago got huge contributions in the run game, racking up 222 yards on the ground.\n\n\r\n              DAndre Swift, coming off a 108-yard outing against Washington, ran for a season-high 124 yards and a <a href=\"https://x.com/ChicagoBears/status/1979970128159617404\">touchdown</a>.\n\n\r\n              Rookie <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4608686/kyle-monangai\">Kyle Monangai</a> added a career-high 81 yards and a <a href=\"https://x.com/ChicagoBears/status/1979975034232873022\">touchdown</a>, helping Chicago stop an eight-game losing streak against the Saints. They hadnt beaten New Orleans since 2008.\n\n\r\n              Rattler was 20 of 32 for 233 yards while throwing three interceptions.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4361370/chris-olave\">Chris Olave</a> caught five passes for 98 yards and two touchdowns. His 57-yard reception near the end of the first half set up a 21-yard TD, and he hauled in a 14-yarder on the opening drive of the third quarter to pull the Saints within 20-14. \n\n\r\n              <hl2>Shut down</hl2>\r\n              Kamara said the Bears didn't pressure as much as he expected, but Allen picked the right moments to dial it up.\n\n\r\n              \"He does well with the things he wants to get to, he said. Got those guys playing physically, and theyre playing pretty sound defense.\n\n\r\n              The Bears held New Orleans to 13 yards before a 91-yard touchdown drive near the end of the half. Olave beat cornerback <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4426374/tyrique-stevenson\">Tyrique Stevenson</a> on a 57-yard reception to the 21, and he hauled in a 21-yard touchdown two plays later, cutting it to 20-7 in the closing minute. \n\n\r\n              The Saints went 80 yards for a touchdown on the opening drive of the second half, with Olave's 14-yarder cutting it to 20-14.\n\n\r\n              Chicago then drove from the 28 to the 1, only to settle for a field goal by <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4372066/jake-moody\">Jake Moody</a> after center <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4242553/drew-dalman\">Drew Dalman</a> got flagged for a false start when he double-clutched on a fourth-down snap at the goal line.\n\n\r\n              Moody, filling in for the second straight game with <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/17427/cairo-santos\">Cairo Santos</a> sidelined by a quad injury, added a 33-yarder midway through the fourth, making it 26-14, and <a href=\"https://x.com/ChicagoBears/status/1979998024395874387\">Edmunds intercepted a tipped pass</a> thrown by Rattler to help seal the win.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Injuries</hl2>\r\n              Saints: RB <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4599739/kendre-miller\">Kendre Miller</a> (knee) and C <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3917331/erik-mccoy\">Erik McCoy</a> (biceps) left the game, and coach Kellen Moore said there's concern for both those guys.\n\n\r\n              Bears: Stevenson (shoulder) and TE <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4258595/cole-kmet\">Cole Kmet</a> (back) exited the game.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Up next</hl2>\r\n              Saints: Host Tampa Bay next Sunday.\n\n\r\n              Bears: At Baltimore next Sunday.\n\n\r\n              ------\n\n\r\n              AP NFL: <a Cleveland's game against Miami that he forgot what it was like to be a part of a win.\n\n\r\n              The Browns safety and his teammates rediscovered that winning feeling on Sunday.\n\n\r\n              Behind a complete effort from all three phases, the Browns rolled to a 31-6 victory over the Dolphins to snap a three-game losing streak.\n\n\r\n              I remember now. Feels good, said Delpit in the locker room after the game. I think it was a huge win, honestly. Just to get one and now to multiply those, we cant keep pinballing around in the season, going up and down.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4685702/quinshon-judkins\">Quinshon Judkins</a> scored three touchdowns as the Browns (2-5) got over the 17-point hump for the first time in 12 games. The defense held an opponent with a touchdown for the first time in nearly two years and special teams forced a key turnover in the second quarter.\n\n\r\n              We always talk about complementary football, but seeing us all come together is important and good to see, said quarterback <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4427238/dillon-gabriel\">Dillon Gabriel</a>, who completed 13 of 18 for 116 yards to get his first NFL win in his first start in front of Cleveland's fans.\n\n\r\n              In a game in which passing was at a premium due to heavy rain and wind during the first half, Judkins became the first Browns running back with three rushing scores in a game since <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3128720/nick-chubb\">Nick Chubb</a> in 2022.\n\n\r\n              Two of the touchdowns came on direct snaps out of the Wildcat formation. Coach Kevin Stefanski said they put that in the game plan late in the week after seeing the weather forecast.\n\n\r\n              On second-and-goal at the Dolphins 3 midway through the second quarter, the <a href=\"https://x.com/Browns/status/1979970723696275713\">rookie running back bobbled the direct snap</a> before hauling it in and running up the middle to extend Cleveland's lead to 17-3.\n\n\r\n              Any predicament puts yourself in the best position to go out there and prepare for that. During the week of practicing with wet balls and our coaches have been putting us in position to succeed,\" said Judkins, who finished with 84 rushing yards on 25 carries, including a <a href=\"https://x.com/Browns/status/1979967036815032752\">46-yard touchdown</a> early in the second quarter to put Cleveland on top.\n\n\r\n              Judkins extended Clevelands lead to 31-6 early in the fourth quarter when he took another direct snap and went 2 yards for the score. \n\n\r\n              The Browns picked off <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4241479/tua-tagovailoa\">Tua Tagovailoa</a> three times and scored 21 points off of Miami's four turnovers. \n\n\r\n              Cornerback <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4379397/tyson-campbell\">Tyson Campbell</a>, acquired from the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/jax/jacksonville-jaguars\">Jacksonville Jaguars</a> on Oct. 9, <a href=\"https://x.com/NFL/status/1979982017292104026\">returned an interception 34 yards for a touchdown</a> on the first play of the second half.\n\n\r\n              Safety <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/2969961/rayshawn-jenkins\">Rayshawn Jenkins</a> had a fumble recovery on special teams in the second quarter and an interception in the fourth. Both of his takeaways set up Judkins' touchdowns out of the Wildcat.\n\n\r\n              Miami (1-6) outgained Cleveland 219-206, but managed just a pair of field goals from <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4243371/riley-patterson\">Riley Patterson</a>. Tagovailoa threw three interceptions for the second straight week and had a career-low passer rating of 24.1 as he completed 12 of 23 for 100 yards. He also fumbled three times, but didn't lose it.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4889929/quinn-ewers\">Quinn Ewers</a> replaced Tagovailoa midway through the fourth quarter after the sixth-year quarterback had his sixth career three-pick game. \n\n\r\n              The Dolphins were 1 of 13 on third down and were penalized 11 times for 103 yards.\n\n\r\n              We did everything we could to lose the game,\" coach Mike McDaniel said. \"You saw a lot of frustration from the season seep into our play. I felt like emotional overreactions in the first half were detrimental to us. Four drives were sustained by penalties defensively.\n\n\r\n              The only bright spot for Miami was running back <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4429160/de'von-achane\">De'Von Achane</a>, who had 13 carries for 82 yards rushing.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Is the end near?</hl2>\r\n              The Dolphins are 29-29 with McDaniel in his fourth season, but questions about his future continue to intensify.\n\n\r\n              A downcast and rambling McDaniel did take exception to those wondering about his job security in Miami.\n\n\r\n              If I'm thinking about having a job, I need to be doing my job, he said. I think it's offensive to all coaches, players and the organization if I'm spending that precious time thinking about myself.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Injuries</hl2>\r\n              Dolphins: TE <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/2576925/darren-waller\">Darren Waller</a> had a pectoral injury in the first half and did not return. ... DE <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3932901/elijah-campbell\">Elijah Campbell</a> (quadricep) and CB <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4427103/storm-duck\">Storm Duck</a> (ankle) were inactive.\n\n\r\n              Browns: DE <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4605792/adin-huntington\">Adin Huntington</a> suffered a concussion in the first half and did not return. ... TE <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3123076/david-njoku\">David Njoku</a> (knee) and OT <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/2979534/jack-conklin\">Jack Conklin</a> (concussion) were inactive. \n\n\r\n              <hl2>Up Next</hl2>\r\n              Dolphins: At Atlanta next Sunday.\n\n\r\n              Browns: At New England next Sunday.\n\n\r\n              ------\n\n\r\n Titans","New England Patriots","New England Patriots @ Tennessee Titans","NFL"],"story":"NASHVILLE, Tenn. --  <a href=\"https://apnews.com/hub/mike-vrabel\">Mike Vrabel</a> greeted his <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/ne/new-england-patriots\">New England Patriots</a> with a celebratory hug just as he did with the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/ten/tennessee-titans\">Tennessee Titans</a> not far away in Nissan Stadium and not too long ago. \n\n\r\n              That's why his Patriots knew just how much winning Sunday meant to Vrabel even if the coach tried to keep the attention on his current team.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4431452/drake-maye\">Drake Maye</a> threw for 222 yards and two touchdowns and the Patriots beat the Tennessee Titans 31-13 Sunday in Vrabel's first game against the franchise that <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/titans-mike-vrabel-fired-7aed662bb18ef9454d6aac275ace4636\">fired him</a> in January 2024.\n\n\r\n              He downplayed it all week, which we appreciate,\" Maye said. \"I think hes focused on us and worried about us, and thats what matters. But I know that it feels good for him.\n\n\r\n              Fans chanted Vrabel, Vrabel as the clock ticked down. One Titans' fan held up a sign apologizing to Vrabel.\n\n\r\n              I didnt get that many tickets, I dont know ..., Vrabel said of the chants. Im happy for our players. I think these guys theyre figuring out how to win, theyre figuring out how to practice. I guess its humbling to have these people whoever that is cheer for us whether that's the Patriots or Drake Maye or me or anybody else.\"\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"https://apnews.com/hub/new-england-patriots\">The Patriots</a> (5-2) won their fourth straight overall and third consecutive on the road. That keeps them atop the AFC East and spoiled Mike McCoy's debut as Tennessee's <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/titans-interim-coach-mike-mccoy-dd27b53151c87d20a4196ae1165029cc\">interim head coach.</a> The Patriots last won this many consecutive games during a seven-game streak in the 2021 season.\n\n\r\n              An emotional game, emotional stretch for us, Vrabel said. Something that this team and organization hasn't done, and it's done a lot. \n\n\r\n              Maye completed 21 of 23 passes for a 135.9 passer rating. He now is the third player under the age of 24 with at least 200 yards passing and a passer rating of 100 or higher in six straight games in NFL history joining <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3139477/patrick-mahomes\">Patrick Mahomes</a> (seven consecutive in 2018) and Pro Football Hall of Famer Dan Marino (six in 1984).\n\n\r\n              Linebacker <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4242205/k'lavon-chaisson\">K'Lavon Chaisson</a> had two of the Patriots' five sacks and returned a fumble 4 yards for a touchdown. <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/titans-release-harold-landry-49edbc826ced2053d21b76ba2ea7c66a\"><a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3122793/harold-landry\">Harold Landry III</a></a> had the final sack against the team that released him in March, and <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4241720/marcus-jones\">Marcus Jones</a> had an interception in the final minutes. \n\n\r\n              <a href=\"https://apnews.com/hub/tennessee-titans\">The Titans</a> (1-6) turned in their best start to a game this season with <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4688380/cam-ward\">Cam Ward</a> looking like the No. 1 pick overall. \n\n\r\n              They scored their fourth TD this season and were up 10-3 after the first quarter. That was more points than they had through six games combined as they were outscored 47-9.\n\n\r\n              That also marked <a href=\"https://x.com/JoshDubowAP/status/1979963455089345001\">Tennessees biggest lead since Week 16</a> of last season when the Titans led the Colts by seven. \n\n\r\n              Were going to stick together here,\" McCoy said. \"We're going to fight our tails off and find a way to go win the next one. Thats the most important thing.\n\n\r\n              Ward also completed 10 of his first 11 passes for 144 yards for more yards by halftime than he managed in two games this season. He finished with 255 yards.\n\n\r\n              Maye gave the Patriots a 17-13 lead at halftime, tossing a 39-yarder to <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4429022/kayshon-boutte\">Kayshon Boutte</a> for his second TD with 49 seconds left. He found <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3043275/austin-hooper\">Austin Hooper</a> for a 3-yard TD earlier in the second quarter.\n\n\r\n              New England blew open the game in the third.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"https://apnews.com/hub/drake-maye\">Maye</a> missed three plays on the opening drive of the third. He went to the sideline after his head bounced off the turf at the end of a 6-yard run and he shook his head once he sat up. The Patriots quarterback to help finish the 88-yard drive with a 4-yard TD run by <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4569173/rhamondre-stevenson\">Rhamondre Stevenson</a>.\n\n\r\n              Just 11 seconds later, <a href=\"https://x.com/NFL/status/1979983366050238887\">Chaisson picked up a ball</a> fumbled by Ward on a sack at the Titans 4 and took it into the end zone for a 31-13 lead. \n\n\r\n              <hl2>Sweet payback</hl2>\r\n              Vrabel and Landry aren't the only Patriots with ties to the Titans, and Chaisson said their teammates wanted to make sure this was a game to enjoy playing in Tennessee. \n\n\r\n              Definitely with some extra juice on the defensive end to make sure that our guys, anybody that ... came from this team or just was a part of this organization in anyway, man, they got their revenge and they came out on top,\" Chaisson said. \n\n\r\n              <hl2>Injuries</hl2>\r\n              Titans three-time Pro Bowl defensive tackle <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4035369/jeffery-simmons\">Jeffery Simmons</a> hurt a hamstring early and did not return. CB <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4040432/l'jarius-sneed\">L'Jarius Sneed</a> hurt a quad in the third quarter and did not return.\n\n\r\n              <hl2>Up next</hl2>\r\n              Patriots start a two-game homestand, hosting Cleveland on Oct. 26.\n\n\r\n              The Titans visit Indianapolis on Oct. 26.\n\n\r\n              ------\n\n\r\n              AP NFL: <a
